proof.p:
We wish to show that if
F(x) &= \int_a^x f(t) \dee{t} & \text{then}&& F'(x) &= f(x)
Assume that F is the above integral and then consider F'(x). By definition
F'(x) &=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0} \frac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h}
To understand this limit, we interpret the terms F(x), F(x+h) as signed areas. To simplify this further, let's only consider the case that f is always nonnegative and that h \gt 0. These restrictions are not hard to remove, but the proof ideas are a bit cleaner if we keep them in place. Then we have
F(x+h)&=\text{the area of the region $\big\{\ (t,y)\ \big|\ a\le t\le x+h,\ 0\le y\le f(t)\ \big\}$}
F(x)&=\text{the area of the region $\big\{\ (t,y)\ \big|\ a\le t\le x, \phantom{+h\ \,}\ 0\le y\le f(t)\ \big\}$}
Then the numerator
F(x+h)-F(x)=\text{the area of $\big\{\ (t,y)\ \big|\ x\le t\le x+h,\ 0\le y\le f(t)\ \big\} $}
This is just the more darkly shaded region in the figure
We will be taking the limit h\rightarrow 0. So suppose that h is very small. Then, as t runs from x to x+h, f(t) runs only over a very narrow range of valuesNotice that if f were discontinuous, then this might be false., all close to f(x).
So the darkly shaded region is almost a rectangle of width h and height f(x) and so has an area which is very close to f(x)h. Thus \frac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h} is very close to f(x).
In the limit h\rightarrow 0, \frac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h} becomes exactly f(x), which is precisely what we want.

example.p:
First, Example gives


         F(x) = \int_0^x  t\,\dee{t} =\frac{x^2}{2}


So of course F'(x) = x. Second, Part1 of the fundamental theorem  of calculus tells us that the derivative of F(x) is just the integrand.  That is, Part1 of the fundamental theorem of calculus also gives F'(x) = x.

Despite this, we can find its derivative by just applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus with f(t)=e^{-t^2} and a=0.  That gives


\diff{}{x}\int_0^x e^{-t^2}\dee{t} &=\diff{}{x}\int_0^x f(t)\dee{t}

&=f(x) = e^{-x^2}

The fundamental theorem tells us how to compute the derivative of  functions of the form \int_a^x f(t)\dee{t} but the integral at hand is  not of the specified form because the upper limit we have is x^2, rather than  x,  so more care is required. Thankfully we can deal with this obstacle with only a  little extra work. The trick is to define an auxiliary function by simply  changing the upper limit to x. That is, define


 E(x) &= \int_0^x e^{-t^2}\dee{t}

Then the integral we want to work with is

  E(x^2) &= \int_0^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}


The derivative E'(x) can be found via part1 of the fundamental theorem of  calculus (as we did in Example) and is E'(x)=  e^{-x^2}. We can then use this fact with the chain rule to compute the  derivative we need:


  \diff{}{x} \int_0^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}  &= \diff{}{x}E(x^2) &\text{use the chain rule}

  &= 2x E'(x^2)

  &= 2x e^{-x^4}

Consider the integral


  \int_x^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}


As was the case in the previous example, we have to do a little pre-processing  before we can apply the fundamental theorem.

Fortunately we can use the basic properties of integrals  (Theorem(b) and(c)) to split \int_x^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}  into pieces whose derivatives we already know.


\int_x^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}
&=\int_x^0 e^{-t^2}\dee{t}+\int_0^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}
&\text{by Theorem }\text{(c)}

&=-\int^x_0 e^{-t^2}\dee{t}+\int_0^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}
&\text{by Theorem }\text{(b)}


With this pre-processing, both integrals are of the right form. Using what  we have learned in the the previous two examples,


\diff{}{x}\int_x^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}
&=\diff{}{x}\left( -\int_0^{x} e^{-t^2}\dee{t} + \int_0^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}  \right)

&=-\diff{}{x}\int^x_0 e^{-t^2}\dee{t} +\diff{}{x}\int_0^{x^2} e^{-t^2}\dee{t}

&=- e^{-x^2} +2x e^{-x^4}

statement.p:
The symbol


\left.\int f(x)\dee{x} \right|_{a}^{b}


denotes the change in an antiderivative of f(x) from x=a to x=b. More precisely,  let F(x) be any antiderivative of f(x). Then


\left.\int f(x)\dee{x} \right|_{a}^{b}
  &= \left.F(x)\right|_a^b = F(b) - F(a)

ul.li:
Now it is straightforward to compute the integral:


\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \sin x\dee{x}
&= \left.-\cos x \right|_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}
\qquad\text{since $-\cos x$ is an antiderivative of $\sin x$}

&= -\cos\frac{\pi}{2}+\cos 0

&= 0+1=1

We're now ready to compute the prescribed integral.


\int_1^2 \frac{1}{x}\dee{x}
&= \left. \log x \right|_1^2 & \text{since $\log x$ is an antiderivative of $1/x$}

&= \log 2 - \log 1 & \text{since $\log 1 = 0$}

&= \log 2

We're now ready to compute the prescribed integral.


\int_{-2}^{-1} \frac{1}{x}\dee{x}
&= \log|x| \bigg|_{-2}^{-1}
\qquad \text{since $\log|x|$ is an antiderivative of $1/x$}

&= \log|-1| - \log|-2| = \log 1-\log 2

&= -\log 2 = \log\frac12.
